editorialDecl.p: EEBO-TCP is a partnership between the Universities of Michigan and Oxford and the publisher ProQuest to create accurately transcribed and encoded texts based on the image sets published by ProQuest via their Early English Books Online (EEBO) database (http://eebo.chadwyck.com). The general aim of EEBO-TCP is to encode one copy (usually the first edition) of every monographic English-language title published between 1473 and 1700 available in EEBO.

EEBO-TCP aimed to produce large quantities of textual data within the usual project restraints of time and funding, and therefore chose to create diplomatic transcriptions (as opposed to critical editions) with light-touch, mainly structural encoding based on the Text Encoding Initiative (http://www.tei-c.org).

The EEBO-TCP project was divided into two phases. The 25,368 texts created during Phase 1 of the project (2000-2009), initially available only to institutions that contributed to their creation, were released into the public domain on 1 January 2015. The approximately 40,000 texts produced during Phase 2 (2009- ), of which 34,963 had been released as of 2020, originally similarly restricted, were similarly freed from all restrictions on 1 August 2020. As of that date anyone is free to take and use these texts for any purpose (modify them, annotate them, distribute them, etc.). But we do respectfully request that due credit and attribution be given to their original source.
Users should be aware of the process of creating the TCP texts, and therefore of any assumptions that can be made about the data.

Text selection was based on the New Cambridge Bibliography of English Literature (NCBEL). If an author (or for an anonymous work, the title) appears in NCBEL, then their works are eligible for inclusion. Selection was intended to range over a wide variety of subject areas, to reflect the true nature of the print record of the period. In general, first editions of a works in English were prioritized, although there are a number of works in other languages, notably Latin and Welsh, included and sometimes a second or later edition of a work was chosen if there was a compelling reason to do so.

Image sets were sent to external keying companies for transcription and basic encoding. Quality assurance was then carried out by editorial teams in Oxford and Michigan. 5% (or 5 pages, whichever is the greater) of each text was proofread for accuracy and those which did not meet QA standards were returned to the keyers to be redone. After proofreading, the encoding was enhanced and/or corrected and characters marked as illegible were corrected where possible up to a limit of 100 instances per text. Any remaining illegibles were encoded as <gap>s. Understanding these processes should make clear that, while the overall quality of TCP data is very good, some errors will remain and some readable characters will be marked as illegible. Users should bear in mind that in all likelihood such instances will never have been looked at by a TCP editor.
The texts were encoded and linked to page images in accordance with level 4 of the TEI in Libraries guidelines.

Copies of the texts have been issued variously as SGML (TCP schema; ASCII text with mnemonic sdata character entities); displayable XML (TCP schema; characters represented either as UTF-8 Unicode or text strings within braces); or lossless XML (TEI P5, characters represented either as UTF-8 Unicode or TEI g elements).
Keying and markup guidelines are available at the Text Creation Partnership web site.

div.head: To the Reader.
div.p: BLinde Bayarde is boldeſt to launch into the deepe, and rashe Souldiour readieſt to giue the firſt aſſault: Though wilful blindneſſe, and headdy rashneſſe be vices intolerable, yet ſuche blindeneſſe and ſuche rasheneſſe (in my iudgement) is cōmendable, as either breaketh the yce vnto the better ſeeing, or treadeth the path to the diſcret and cunning. This perſwaſion hath made me preſume to Englishe this worke: and this mine onſet hereafter may prouoke the skilfull to perfit the ſame. In the mean while (good Reader) vſe it to thy profit, ſo shalt thou encourage me (according to my skill and leaſure) to further thy ſtudies.

list.item: A The first letter ſerueth many times to expreſſe the Datiue caſe: as, Ie l'ay donné à mon pere. J gaue it to my father: Sometime it ſerueth for the prepoſition, To: as, Ie m'en vay à mon pere, J go to my father.
Eſtre plus aagé qu'vn autre, To be older than an other.
Abandonner, to giue ouer, or to licence, to cast off.
Abaſtardir, corrompre, to corrupt or abastardiſe, to counterfeat.
Abbatre, to beate downe, throwe downe, or hurle downe.
Abbayeur, a barker, a teller of faultes.
Abbaiſſer, to abaſe or bring low.
Abbaiſſement de voix, a ſpeaking ſofte.
Vn abbregé, an abstract, a ſhort, ſumme.
Abbreuer les cheuaux, to water horſes.
Vn a b c, an a b c.
Abolir, to abolish, to diſalow, to abrogate.
Aboli, hors d'vſage, aboliſhed, or out of vſe.
Auoir en abhommation, to abhorre, to loath, to despiſe.
Abonder, to abound, to flowe, to be plentifull.
Aborder, to ariue at, or common and talke with, to lande at any place.
Aboutir, quand quelque apoſtume aboutit, to draw to hed or wax ripe, whē an apoſtume draweth to head.
Aboutir à quelque lieu, to draw to ſome place.

Aboutiſſemēt de terres, the end
or limittes of any ground.
Abri, ou le ſoleil frappe touſiours, a ſunny banke.
Abſenter, to abſent, to be abſent.
Abſolution & declaration de n'auoir commis aucune faulte an abſolution.
Abuſer de quelque choſe, To miſuſe or abuſe a thing.
Abuſer aucun, to miſuſe a man, or deceyue him.
Acariaſtre, to be madde, or oute of our wit, to be furious.
Acabler quelqu'vn, to ſnarle or entrap a man.
Accez, Facile accez & entrée enuers aucun, eaſy commyng or entry to any man.
Accez de fiebure, a fitte of an Ague.
Accident, pour circonſtance, ou qualite, & auſsi aduerſité, a hap, a chaunce, a fortune.
Accointāce & familiarité qu'on à les vns auec les autres, acquaintance and familiaritie.
Accoinctement, mot peu vſité, an attonement.
Accoiſer, to aſſuage, to appeaſe, to mitigate.
Qui n'eſt point Accoiſé, which is not yet appeaſed.
Accoller, to coll, to kiſſe, to imbrace.
vne Accollée doulce & amoureuſe, a ſweete and louely embracing.
s'Accommoder au temps, To frame himſelfe to the time.
Accompaigner aucun, to company, to kepe felowſhip.
Accomplir, to fulfill, to finiſhe or ende, to performe.

Accorder, to agree, to conſente,
to graunt.
Accorder ſa fille en mariage, ou ſon fils, to betrouth or make ſure a ſonne or daughter.
Vn ſon accordant, a concorde in tune.
vne Accordée, a Mayde made ſure.
Accord de ſons & choſes differentes, agreing of diſagreing things.
Accord & conuenance, a couenant or agreement.
Accord & conſentement, an agreement or conſent.
Accord, paction, conuention, a bargayne or compoſition.
Accordailles, a betrouthing or making ſure.
on fera Accordailles, they ſhall be made ſure.
Accoſter, to prop or ſtay vp, to reare.
Accoſté & appuyé contre vne arbre, ſtayed vp againſt a tree, reared vp.
Accoucher d'enfant, to lye in chylde bed.
Femme qui accouche de ſon premier, ſhee that lyeth in of hir first childe.
vne Accouchée & giſante, a child bed wyfe.
Accouplre, to ioyne, or yoke togither.
Accouplement de boeufs, a yoking of oxen.
Accourber, to crooke, or make croked, to bend.
Accourir de toutes parts, To runne from all partes.
Accourement & aſſemblement de gents, a running togither, or aſſemblie of men.
s'Accouſter à l'oreille d'aucun to whisper in a mans eare.
Accouſtrer, to decke, to triname, to dreſſe.
Accouſtumer, to custome, or to enure.
s'Accouſtumer, to vſe, to cuſtom himſelfe.
Accrocher, to graſpe, or to catch.
Accroire quelque argent, To trust money.
Accroiſtre, to encreaſe, to augment, to multiplie.
Accueillir, to approch to a man, to come nere.
De l'ache, Perſelye, ſome ſaye, Smallage.
Acheter, to buye, to redeme, to bargayne.
Acheuer, to ende, to conclude, to finiſhe.
Vne achoiſe fort grande, a very good occaſion.
Acquiſition de la Seigneurie, the gettyng of the lordſhyp by preſcription.
Acquieſcer à ce qui eſt iugé, S'accorder et obeir de la ſentence, to ſtande to the iudgemente, to agree to the ſentence.
S'acquiter, to be quit, to diſpatch, to ridde or vnburthen.
Acquitté de ſon ſerment, free or quit of an othe.
Faire quelque choſe laſchemēt, & per manier d'acquit, ſeulement pour en eſtre deſpeché to doo a thyng ſleyghtly with riddance only to be dispatcht of it.
Eſtre fort actif, to be actiue.
Action & beſongne, a dede or woorke.
Action & droict de pourſuyure en iuſtice ce qui nous eſt deü, an action in lawe.
S'addōner à faire quelque choſe to bee giuen or bente to anye thing.
Addonné à Amour, giuen to loue.
Addoubeur de mauuaiſes cauſes, a forger of euill cauſes.
Addoulcir, to aſſuage, to appeaſe, to mitigate, to attone.
A denerer & apprecier à argēt, to priſe.
Qui adioinct, a ioyner to, an adder too.
Adionction, a ioyning to, an addition.
Adiourner aucun, to ſummon a man.
Adiouſter, to adde, to put to.
Adiuger, to adiuge, to giue ſentence.
Adminiſtrer & gouuerner vne prouince, to gouerne or rule a prouince.
Admoneſter, to admoniſh, to warne, to charge.
Adoleſcent ou Adoleſcente, a yong man or mayd.
Adonc, than or at that tyme.
Adopter & prendre à fils, to adopt, or to make one my ſon.
Adreſſer quel qu'vn au chemin, to ſet one in the right waye, to direct.
Vne adreſſe & courſiere, a short or direct way.
Aduenir, to happen, to chance, to betyde, to come to paſſe.
Il eſt aduenu, it happened, it chaunced, it came to paſſe.
Qui eſt aduenu & commis, which came to paſſe, or was committed.
Aduenture, a chaunce, a fortune, an aduenture.
Aduerſité, aduerſitie, mishappe, misfortune, ill ſucceſſe.
Aduertir, to aduertiſe, to warne, to declare.
A mon adueü, on my worde, on my fidelitie.
Aduis & opinion, aduiſe, counſell or iudgement.
Aduiſer, to aduiſe, to conſider, to determine.
Aduiſer aucun, to giue one aduiſe
Aduiſement & eſgard qu'on a à faire quelque choſe, taking aduiſe or waryneſſe in doing any thing.

Vn Adultere, an adulterer, one that committeth whoredome in
mariage.
Aduocat, an Aduocate, an attorney, a procurator.
Aduocaſſer pour aucun, & le defendre en iugement, to plead or ſtande in a mannes cauſe.
Aduouër quelque crime & confeſſer l'auoir commis, to auouche a crime, or confeſſe the deed.
C'eſt ton Affaire, it is thy matter, it ſtandeth thee vpon.
s'Affaiſſer, to be ouerladen, to ſhrinke.
Affaiſement de quelque grāde choſe peſante quand elle s'eſt abaiſſée & affaiſſée, a ſhrinking vnder a great burthen, an ouerburthening, a quelling.
Affamer vne ville, to famiſhe a towne.
Affecter de ſe mettre en la male grace d'aucun, to get the ill will of any man.
Affection, affection, deſire, will, the diſeaſe of the mynd.
Affermer, to affirme, to cōfirme, to aſſure.
Affermir, to fortifie, to make firme, to ſtabliſh.
Affiert ou conuient, it behoueth or beſeemeth.
Affin, write afin, that, or to the end that.
Affiner les fins, to beguyle the crafty.
Affins & alliez par mariage, kin or allies.
Affiquets de nulle valeur, tryfles, toyes, trinkets.
Affliger & vexer, ou tourmēter, to afflict, to greeue or torment.
Entreprendre de s'Affoler ſoymeſme, to goe about to hurte himſelfe.
Affoler pour bleſſer, to hurt, to fell one downe.
Affranchir vn ſeruiteur, & luy donner liberté, to ſet a Seruant at libertie.
Affriander, Affrioler, to cocker, to make likeriſhe, to pamper.
Vn Affronteur & Abuſeur, a deceyuer, a beguyler.
Affubler, to clothe, ſometime to muffle.
Affublement & conuerture, a clothing or couering.
Agaçer aucun, to egge, to ſtirre, to prouoke.
Agaçement de dents, ſetting the teeth on edge.
Agençer to make fitte, iust, or apt.
Aggluer, to ioyne, to glue, to ſouder togither.
Aggrandir, to make great, to enlarge.
Aggrauanter, to aggrauate, or make heynous.
Il n'Aggree point à l'oreille du commun populaire, it lyketh not the common people.
Aggreger, to aſſemble, to gather togither.
Agir perſonnellement, to aſſigne perſonally, or to appoint.
Agitation & eſmouuement, mouing, working, exerciſing, toſſing.
Vne Agraphe, a boucle of a girdle, a claspe, a brace, a grapple.
Agreſlir ſa voix, to ſqueake out, or or ſing ſhrill.
Aguille à couldre, a ſowing neelde.
Aguillon, a pricke or goad, a ſting.
Aguillonner, to pricke forward, to ſtirre, to prouoke.
Aguillōneur, a pricker forward, a ſtirrer, a mouer.
Aguiſer, to sharpe, to whet, to grind.
Aheurté en fon opinion, obstinate in opinion, ſelfe willed, ſtifnecked.
Aheurtement, Le vice d'obſtination, obstinacie, ſelfe willedneſſe.
Ahy, mot qui ſe dit quand on a peur, out alas.
Aider, to help, to aſſist, to further, to ſet forward, to ſuccour.
Qui Aide, a helper, or furtherer.
Aigret, tirant vn peu ſur l'aigre, tart, or almost ſoure.
S'aigrir, to waxe ſoure, or tart.
Aigrir & irriter aucun, to ſtirre or moue one to anger.
Les ailes qu'on baille à vn cheual, to giue a horſe the heade.
Aile d'oyſeau, ou d'autre beſte qui vole, the wing of a byrde or any other beast that flyeth.
Vne pierre appellée Aimant, the load ſtone.
Aimer, to loue, to delight in any thing.
Aimant, a louer, a ſweet hart.
Digne d'eſtre Aymé, worthy to be loued.
Ainſi, euen ſo, after the ſame mā ner.
Ainſi comme, euen as, as it were.
L'aire d'vne granche, the floure of a barne.
Longues Aires és iardins, a bed in a garden.
Eſtre debonnaire, & ſans malice, to be gentle and without malice.
Aiſné, the first borne, or eldest childe.
Aiſé à faire, eaſie to be done.
Eſtre fort aiſé en ſon meſnage, to be well ſettled.
Il prend ſes aiſes, he taketh his eaſe.
Aiſſelle, ou les ailes, the arme-holes.
Vne aleſne, an aule, a bodkin.
Alicté perpetuelement de maladie, he that lyeth bedred.
Aliener & eſtranger, to alienate, to make ſtrange, to take away.
Alienation, an alienation or making away.
Alignemēt, a Card or draught, Prendre les alignements, & meſmes d'vne ville, to take the draught of a town.
Aliſier, a tree that groweth in Afrike, and is called a lote tree.
Qui allaicte, She that giueth ſucke.
Alleguer fauſement & malieuſement, ou mettre à ſus quelque choſe à quelqu'vn, to alleadge falſely, or to laye to ones charge.
Alleguer ſes moyens, cauſes & raiſons, to alleadge the cauſes,
Alleger, to heaue vp, to eaſe, to ſuccour, to lighten.
Aller, to go, to walke, to wend, to iourney.
Aller à pied, to go a iourney on foote.
Aller à Cheual, to go by horſe, to ryde.
Aller au deuant, to meet with.
Aller contre aucun par fureur, to go furiouſly agaynst one.
Aller apres aucun, to goe after one.
Aller vers aucun, to goe towardes one.
Aller ça & la de coſté & d'autre, to wander, to go hither and thither, to ſtray.
Aller ius, to run headlong, to decay.
Allée, an alley, a path, a way.
Allée ou Gallerie, & autre lieu ou on ſe pourmene, an alley or gallerie, a walking place.
s'Allier auec aucun, to plight friendſhip with any, to ioyne with an other.
Fort Allié & grand ami, very great friends.
Peuples Alliez, people confederate, brethren, fellowes.
Faire Alliance, to make alliance, to make peace.
Allumer, to lighten, to kindle, to enflame.
Aloſe, a fiſh named a loch • .
Aloy, money, alley or value of golde or ſiluer.
Les Alpes, montaynes in Italie called the Alpes.
Par Alternations & chāgemens d'ans, by altering and chāging of yeares.
Amadouër & apaiſer de belles parolles, to delite, to flatter with faire wordes.
Amadoüeur, a flatterer, a faire ſpeaker.
Amadoüement, flatterie, faire ſpeache, lulling on ſleape.
s'Amaigrir, deuenir greſle & menu, to waxe leane or thin.
l'Amarri ou matrice d'vne femme, the wombe or matrix of a woman.
Amas, mōceau, & tas, a heape, a number, a ſorte, a rout.
Amas de blé, a heape of corne.
grand Amas de bois, a great pile of wood.
Amas de geus & aſſemblée, a great number of people.
Amaſſer, to gather togither, to heape togither.
s'Amaſſer, to agree or gather in one.
Qui eſt Amaſſé & amoncelé, which is gathered and heaped.
Amathyſte, pierre precieuſe, a precious ſtone called Amatiſt.
Ambiguemēt parler à deux ententes, dire parolles doubteuſes, par leſquelles on ne ſçait qu'entēdre, to ſpeak doubtfully, or with double vnderſtāding.
Ambitieux, qui brigue & pourchaſſe honneurs, ambitiouſe.
Aller les Ambles, to amble, to goe roundly.
Condamner à l'Amende, to cō demne one to paye a fyne.
Demander l'Amendemēt d'aucun mesfaict à lēcōtre d'aucū, to demaund recōpenſe of a mā.
Amenement, mot peu vſité, a bringing in.
Amenuiſer, to make thin, to make ſlender.
Ameſnager ſa maiſon, to furniſh a houſe.
Amieller le peuple par doulces parolles, & luy deſrober le cueur, to entiſe the people with faire words, and to win their hartes.
Amignotter, to prank or to trim
Amonceler, to gather, to heape togither.
Racourci & amoncelé, ſhortned or brought in leſſe roome.
Amoncellement, a gathering togither, a heaping.
s'Amuſer à veoir vn danfeur par deſſus la chorde, to ſpend the time to ſee one daūce on a cor ••
Amuſer aucun, to ſette one in • domp, to buſie one.
Ancien, auncient, old, of long cō tinuance.
Vn Ancre à retenir les nauires, an ancre.
Ancrer au port, to cast ancre.
s'Aneantir & ne tenir compte de ſoy, to abaſe or not esteeme himſelfe.
Le bō & mauuais Ange que les Payens eſtimoyēt eſtre d'eux dieux priuez, & familiers, qui s'appliquoyēt à vn chaſcū dés l'heure de ſa naiſsāce, a ghost.
L'herbe qu'on appelle Angelique, an herbe called Angelica.
Vn Anglet, ou coing de toutes choſes, the corner of any thing.
Angler vne perſonne, & ſerrer à l'eſtroict, to ſhut one vp in a corner.
Animer & inciter à ſon de fleutes les gents à frapper, to encourage, or harten men to fight by the ſound of a flute.
Anneau qu'on met au doigt, a ring.
Vn Anneau ou cachet, a ſealing ring.
Annelet qu'on met au doigt, a gimmew.
Eſtre tellemēt Annichilé, qu'l n'ē demeure point vn, ſo vaniſhed away, that nothīg remain.
Anoncer deuant, to giue warning before.
Anōcer quelque choſe aduenir, to foreſhowe a thing.
Annōcement de quelque choſe aduenir, ou aduertiſſement, the foreſhewing of a thing.
s'Annonchalir, Aneantir, to pine away, to weare away.
La grand tāte de coſté paternel the great aunt on the fathers ſide.
Antidater vne obligatiō, to giue an antidate to an obligation.
De l'Antimonion, a ſtone or earth called Antimonium.
Vn Antrac, ou charbon, a coale, alſo a ſore called a carbuncle, sōtim a precious ſtone ſo named
Apertement, openly, manifestly, playnly, without diſſimulatiō.
Apoſtres, c'eſt à dire meſſangers, ou ambaſſades, apostles, meſſangers.
Apoſtumer & meurir, to empoſtume, to runne.
Appaiſer & addoulcir aucun, to appeaſe, to aſſwage, to pleaſe, to pacifie, to quiet.
S'appaiſer, to be quiet, to be pacified and aſwaged.
Appareiller, to decke, to trimme, to furniſh, to prepare.
Eſtre preſt, appareillé, to be ready, or at a becke.
Apparenté, good kinred, a man of a good houſe.
Apparier, to couple, to matche, to appoynt togither.
De l'Aparitoire, ou de la parietaire, herbe croiſſant ſur les' murs, an herbe called Parietory, commonly Pellitorie.
Apparoir, ou Apparoiſtre, to appeare, to ſeeme.
Faire Apparoir vne choſe & monſtrer, to cauſe a thing to ſeeme or ſhewe.
Apparoiſſance & apparence de valeur ou de vice qui reluit en ieuneſſe, the ſhew, dispoſition, or towardneſſe of childrē.
l'Apparoiſſance de quelque choſe qui paſſe oultre vne autre, the apparance or excellencie of one thing by an other.
Appartenance d'vn chacun, the due or propertie of a man.

Le Chaton, dedens quoy eſt la pierre precieuſe enchaſſée, the broad part of the ring where the ſtone is ſet.
Vn Chaudrō de cuyure, ou marmite, ou vne chaudiere, a caudron, a kettle,
Chauffer, to chafe, to heat, too warme.
Tenir chaudemēt quelq̄ choſe, & l'entretenir en ſa chaleur, to keepe hote, or to maintaine a thing in heat.
La Chaſſée & leuée d'vn eſtang ou riuiere, the cauſey of a pond or riuer.
Chauſſetrappe, a calthrop for warre, made like three yron pricks, ſo ioyned, that being throwen, one alwayes ſtandeth vpright.
Vne herbe qu'ō appelle chauſſetrape: c'eſt auſſi vn fruit qu'ō appelle Chaſtaigne de riuiere ou truffes, ou faligots, a brāble
Chauueſouris, a Backe, ſome call it a Batte.
Mettre à Chef quelque haulte enterpriſe, to bring ſome great enterpriſe to paſſe.
Venir à Chef de ſes beſongnes & enterprinſes, to bring the work and enterpriſe to an end
Faire Chef d'oeuure, to make a pincipal peece of worke, too make a maisters peece.
Celidoine ou eſclere, an herbe called Selandine.
Chemin, a waye, a path, a ſtreet.
Chemin, ou rue, a way or ſtreet.
Cheminer, to walke, to iourney, to goe.
Chenille, a worme with many feet that eateth vines, alſo a ſnayle.
Cheant ou tombant, falling or decaying.
Cher & fort aimé, deere and wel beloued.
Vne choſe chere, a deere thing.
Faire grand chere, to make good cheere, to be merie.
Des cheruis, a roote called Skirwike.
Cheualier, ou homme d'armes, a Knight, or man at armes.
Cheualier de l'ordre, a Knight of the order.
La cheuance d'aucun, richeſſe, or goods.
Cheueul, ou poil, ou perruque, a heare.
Cheuet, ou trauerſin d'vn lict, a bolster.
Cheuir auec aucun, to make an end with one.
Vn cheuron, a cheuron, a rafter in the houſe that beareth vp the roofe.
Chez moy, with me, at my houſe
Chiche, a niggard, a pinch pēny.
Vn Chien, ou vne chienne, a dogge, or bitch.
Chier, to go to the ſtoole, to doo our eaſe.
Chimere, a darke or ſuttle imagination.
Le Choc de gents de guerre, a ſhock or brunt of warriours.
Chocquer, to ſtrike, or knocke togither.
Chomer, to tary for, to make holy day for lacke of worke.
Vne chopine, a meaſure conteyning about a quart.
Chou pour chou, like for like.
Chucas, ſorte d'oyſeau, a chough a dawe, a cadeſſe.
De la cichorée, Sichorie, an herb
Le Ciel, the heauen, the skie, ſomtime the ſeeling of a bedde.
Le ciel & peau qui couure les yeux deſſoubs & deſſus en les clignant, the eye liddes.
Ciller à quelqu'vn, to wynke on one.
Vn circuit, a circuit, a compaſſe.
Circution de parolles, a cōpaſſing in with wordes.
Vn ciron, a worme in a mannes hande.
Ciſeau de quoy on fait inciſion ciſſers to make inciſion.
Ciſeaux, ou forces, ciſſers or ſheares.
Vne ciſterne ou l'eaue du ciel chet, a cesterne.
Ciuil, qui ſçait bien ſon entregent, ciuill, or one that knoweth good behauiour.
Vne ciuiere à col, à porter images, & reliques, & autres choſes ſacrées, a coller aboute ones necke, to carry relikes or images on.
Claquer des mains en ſigne de faueur, to clap the handes.
Claqueter des dens, to chatter with the teeth.
Claquette comme celle des ladres, a clapper.
Claye doſier, a lattiſſe of wick • r, a hurdle.
Cler, manifeſt & euident, de quoy on n'a point de doubte, cleere, manifest, euident.
Vn clere qui ſert pour eſcrire, a Clarke.
Il eſt bon Clere, He is learned, he is a good Clarke.
Client, qui s'eſt donné en la tutelle & protectiō de quelque grand ſeigneur, lequel prend la defenſe de toutes ſes affaires à l'encontre de tous, A Client.
Cligner les yeux, to winke, to twinkle with the eye.
Climat & diuiſion du ciel, climate or diuiſion of heauen.
Vn cloiſtre & lieu enuironné de pillers, a Cloyster.
Cloporte & vn eſpece de vermine ſe procreāt és lieux humides & vapoureux comme bains, a worme hauing a great many of feete, a palmer.
Clorre, to cloſe vp, to ſhut vp.
Ce qui eſt clos, that whiche is cloſed.
Cloſture de hayes, a cloſing in in with hedges.
Cloiſon fait du mortier, a mud wall.
Cloiſon faicte d'ais de bout & trauerſants, a bourd wall.
Vn cloüette, a little nayle, a ſprig
Cloüer contre vn croix, to naile on a Croſſe.
Vn coche ou cren, A nicke, a notche.
Vn coeffe, a Coyfe, a night cap.
Coëtiuer, eſchauffer, & entretenir en chaleur, to kepe warm to maynteyne in heate.
Coenne de lard, a bakon skin.
Cognoiſtre, to know, to perceiue to diſcerne, to vnderstand.
Bailler ou donner à cognoiſtre & à entendre manifeſtement, to giue to vnderstande, to declare.
Cognoiſtre parfaictement ou vrayement vne choſe d'entre vne autre, to knowe one thing from an other.
La cho • e eſt ſçeüe & cogneüe, that which is known and come to light.
Coigner, to coyne in, to driue in.
Le coing de toutes choſes, the corner of any thing.
Vn coing à fendre bois, a wedge to cleaue wood.
Vne pomme de coing, a quince.
Des coignaſſes, a kind of quince.
Vn collet, ou gorgias de quoy les femmes couurent leurs poictrines, a partlet.
Collier & autre bague pendant au col, a coller or carket.

Vn collier qu'on met aux chi •
̄s, principalement de chaſſe, A dog coller.
Vn collier à cheuaux, A horſe coller.
La colique, a collāder, a ſtrainer
Collation & taille, a ioyning togither, a tayle.
Collation, Banquette d'aupres ſoupir, a collation, a bankee after ſupper.
Collemēt, a glewing or coupling togither.
Collection, a collection, a gathering togither.
Colluder & faire ſemblant de plaider cōtre aucun, & neantmoins s'entendre auec luy, to make ſemblant to doo a thyng, and do cleane contrarie.
Colporter, porter ſur le col, to carrie a coarſe to buriall.
Le combat & battaille, ou debat, the combat or battaile, the ſtryfe.
Preſenter ou donner le combat to bid the combat.
Combatre & batailler, to fight togither, to battaile.
Combatre en quelque maniere que ce ſoit, to fight.
Le comble, ce qui eſt adiouſté oultre la iuſte meſure, abundance, or that whiche is more than the iust meaſure, ſomtime fulneſſe.
Combler, to fil full, to ouerheap.
Combien eſtes vous? howe many are ye?
Combien penſes tu auoir toſt faict? how ſoone thinkest thou to haue done?
Combien y a-il? how long is it agone?
Comedie & farce, a Comedie, a play, an interlude.
Comete ou eſtoile cheuelüe, a Comete or blaſing ſtarre.
Comin, vne ſorte d'herbe, Comin, an herbe.
Commander & ordonner, To commaunde, to appoynt, to eſtabliſhe.
Commander de faire, to commaunde, to enioyne.
Commandement & ordōnance a commandement, an ordinaunce.
Comme on dit, as men ſay, as it is reported.
Comme ſi ie y euſſe eſté, euen as though J had ben there.
Comme s'il eſtoit faict, as if it were done.
Commencer à faire quelque choſe, to begin a thing, to take a thing in hande.
Commenſal, qui boit & menge ordinairement auec nous, a dayly companion at table.
Comment te portes tu? Howe dost thou? how farest thou?
Commettre quelque choſe à au cun, Le commetre ſus quelque affaire, to commyt a buſineſſe to one.
Commetre quelque vilain ou meſchant cas, to committe a wicked crime.
Commis ſus quelque affaire, apointed to ſome buſineſſe.
Le commiſſaire donné par le Magiſtrat pour cognoiſtre & iuger d'vne cauſe, a Commiſſioner appoynted by the magistrate to heare and iudge a matter.
Donner commiſſaire, To appoynt a commiſſioner.
Commun & appartenant à tous common to all.
Vn commun dict du temps paſſé, A common ſaying of olde tyme.
Communion, communion, a fellowſhip or knitting togither.
Communiquer, to communicate, to make partaker, to conferre.
Compaignon à apprendre, ou d'apprentiſſage, a ſchoolefelow or fellow in houſe.
Compaignon de table, a table fellow.
Compaignon à cheminer, A walking mate.
Compaignon de table à boire & à manger, & à ioüer, a companion bothe at meate and at play.
Compaignon en tous labeurs & peines, a felow in al troubles
Compaignable, one whoſe companie is eaſie to be gotten.
Se comparer à vn autre, to compare with an other.
Comparager & paragoner, To compare, to lyken.
Comparer vne faulte, & payer bien cher, to puniſh a fault.
Comparoir au iour de la monſtre, to appeare in muſter.
Comparoiſtre en iugement, to appere in iudgement.
Ne comparoiſtre point au iour de l'aſsignation dōné par deuant le Magiſtrat, not to appeare at the day appointed by the magistrate.
Compenſer, to recompence, to make amendes.
Faire cher comperre l'offence, to abye for the offence deerly.
Competer & appertenir, to belong or appertaine.
Se complaindre, to complayne, to finde himſelfe greued.
Se complaindre à ſon amy, To complayn to his frende.
Complaint, a complaint or mone making, or bewayling.
Complaint qu'on fait à aucun, d'vn autre, a complaint of an other, a tell tale.
La complexion d'aucun, the cō plexion.
Mal complexionné, yll manered of yll behauiour.
Complot & intelligence qu'on a l'vn auec l'autre, agreement.
Accord & complot faict entre pluſieurs, agreement betweene many.
Compoſer quelque liure, To make a booke.
Compoſer & eſcrire des vers, to make verſes.
Compoſer auec aucun, to compounde with one.
Compoſé & faict de deux natures, compounde and made of two natures.
La compoſition de quelque liure, the making of any Booke.
Compoſition & confection, a compound, a confection.
Compoſition & accord, a compoſition and agreement.
Comprendre, to comprehend, to perceyue, to compaſſe, to vnderſtande.
Eſtre comprins au nombre des bienheureux, to bee compriſed in the numbre of the happy.
Compromettre & ſe rapporter au iugement de quelque arbitre ius quelque different, to put the differēce in arbitremēt.
Compter, to compt, to recken, to number.
Vne compt, a compt, a reckning.

Compte & payement, a reckening,
a payment.
Abbreger ſon compt, to cut off his reckening.
Qui tient le compte, that keepeth the reckening.
Dreſſeur de compte, an accompt caster.
Comptoir & table, ou anciēnemēt les argentiers comptoyent, a counter, or table to cast accompt on.
Cela concerne l'vtilité publique, that concerneth the publike weale.
Conceuoir en ſon eſprit, to conceiue with himſelfe.
Ce qui eſt conçeu, that which is conceiued.
La conception de noſtre entē dement, the ſence, feeling, or perceyuing.
Vn cōcierge ou portier, a porter
Faire bonne concoction, to haue good digestion.
Concupiſcence, concupiſcence, feruent deſire or appetite.
Concurrence, a rūning togither, or agreement.
Condemnation d'amende, An amercing, or putting to fine.
Condeſcendre & s'accorder à quelque choſe, to condeſcende or agree to a thing.
Baſſe condition, of a poore ſtock.
Soubs & par telle condition, on this condition.
Conditions d'vne homme bonnes & mauuaiſes, the conditions or qualities of a good or euill man.
Conduire, to conduct, to gouern, to leade, to traine.
Cōduit à mener l'eaue en quelque lieu, a Cundyte.
Tu es le conducteur de c'eſt affaire, thou art the mayster of all this miſchief, or this worke.
Confiction ou confiture, a confection or confiting.
Confermer, to confirme, to eſtabliſhe, to auoutche.
Confermer ſon opinion, to confirme his opinion.
Confeſſer franchement & ſans contrainte, to confeſſe freely, and without constraint.
On confeſſe bien qu'il eſt vray, it is confeſſed to be true.
Par la confeſſion d'vn chaſ ••• , ſont deshonneſtes, they are vnhonest by the confeſſion of all men.
Se confier, to trust, to put confidence in.
Cōfiner aulcun en quelque lieu & le bannir, to limite one within certain boundes.
Confiſquer les biens d'aucun confiſcate ones goodes, to ſeaſe on forfayte them vnto the Prince.
Confiſcation, ou biens confiſquez, & publication des biens d'aucun, ou de pluſieurs, A confiſcation.
Vne conflant, ou deux riuieres s'aſſemblent, a place where two riuers mete togither.
Conflit & combat, a conflict or combat.
Confondre, meſler enſemble, & broüiller, to confounde, to mingle, to tumble togither.
Se confermer & accorder à aucun, to conforme, or to becom agreeable to an other.
Conforter, & cōfermer les gēts 〈◊〉 guerre, to comforte and encourage warriours.
Confronter l'vn a l'autre, pour en voir la comparaiſon, to cō pare one by an other, to ſee the difference.
Confus, qui n'eſt point diuiſé ne ſeparé, cōfuſed, not diſtinct
Eſtre confus, to bee confuſed, or amazed.
Confuſion & trouble, ou deſordre de toutes choſes, confuſion, trouble, or diſorder in any thing.
Sans mon congé, withoute my leaue.
Congedier vne armée, to breake vp an army.
Il ſe congrege en pierre precieuſe, Jt groweth to a precious ſtone.
Conioindre, to ioyne togither, to glewe togither, to past togither, to fasten.
Coniunction, a ioyning togither, a coniunction.
Coniurer & adiurer aucun, Le prier pour l'amitié, ou autres choſes, to entreat one, on all friendſhip to vtter ſome thing.
Coniurer, Iurer enſemble pour mal faire à aucun, Faire conſpiration, to conspire.
Vn connin, ou connil, a conny, a rabbet.
Conſacrer, to conſecrate, to dedicate, to hallowe.
Conſacré à Dieu, dedicated to God.
Conſacré, ou ſainct, dedicated or hallowed.
Dire en ſa conſcience, to ſay of conſcience.
Faire Conſcience de quelque choſe, to make conſcience of a matter, to ſticke at a matter.
Demander conſeil, to aske coū cell.
Conſeiller, to councell, to warne, to charge, to aduiſe.
Se conſeiller de quelque affaire, to conſult on a matter, to take aduiſement.
Cōſeillier de ville, a counſailour of a Citie.
Cōſeillier de la ville de Rome, a Counſailour of the Citie of Rome.
Conſulter, to conſult, to take aduiſe.
Conſentir à aucun, to conſent to one, to agree.
Choſe graue & de cōſequence, a matter of weight and conſequence.
Conſiderer quelque choſe, too conſider, to weigh, to ponder.
Conſigner, to appoint, to exhibite, to preſent.
Conſiſter, to conſist, or to be.
Cecy conſiſte à chercher la verité, this conſisteth in ſearching the truthe.
Conſoler, to comfort, to cheariſh, to ſolace, to cheare.
Cōſommer & parfaite, to make perfite, to end, to fulfill.
Conſpirer & eſtre de cōmun accord, ſe vnir & allier ensēble pour faire quelque choſe, ſoit bonne ou mauuaiſe, to conſpire, to conſent, to agree.
Conſtellation & aſſemblée d'eſtoilles enſemble en quelque ſigne, a gathering togither of ſtarres into ſome ſigne.
Conſtituer aucun conſul ſus le peuple, to chooſe or apointe a Conſull ouer the people.
Conſtitu, arreſt & determināce de quelq̄ choſe, laquelle apres auoir eſté diſceptée & debatue, eſt miſe à fin, a constitution, an ordinance.
Conſumer, to conſume, to wast, to weare away.
Cōſuiure & atteindre, to follow, to ouertake, to get, to obtayne.
Contaminer, to ſpot, to ſtayne, to defile, to corrupt.
Conte, ou conteſſe, an Earle, a Conteſſe.
Vne conte, deuis & propos, ſoit vray au faux qu'on fait à plaiſir, a fable.
Conte des choſes veritables, a ſtorie.
Vn conteur de contes, fables & ſornettes, a tale teller.
Cōtemner, to deſpiſe, to diſdain, to neglect.
Contēplement, quand on penſe ſoigneuſement à vne choſe, to muſe on a matter.
Contenir & comprēdre, to containe, to comprehend.
Cōtenir & garder de faire oultre, to restraine, to with hold.
Se contenir & moderer, too forbeare, to moderate.
La contenance, the gesture, cō tenance, or behauiour.
Eſtre cōtent de ce qu'on a, to be content with that we haue.
Ie ſuis content, I am content.
I'en ſuis content, J am content.
Mal content, not contēt, displeaſed, offended.
Contenter aucun, to pleaſe or ſatisfie one.
Contentement de peu & abſtinence de voluptez, to bee content with a little.
Cōteſter cauſe ſus quelque different, to make protestation of ſute before the Judge.
Par vn cōtexte, Tout d'vn train, Sans rien meſler, continually togither.
Continu à quelque choſe faire comme s'il eſtoit touſiours ſoubs le ioug, the continuance of a thing.
Continuer, to continue, to goe forward, to last.
Contract, a cōtract, a couenant, a bargaine.
Contracts & conuentions redigées par eſcript, agreements or conuenants put in writing.
Contracter, to contract, too bargayne, to agree.
Contraindre aucun, to cōſtraine, to enforce, to compell.
Eſtre contrainct par neceſſité, to be constrayned or driuen by neceſſitie.
Sans contraincte, without conſtraint, freely, willingly.
Contrecedule, the counterpane of a writing.
Il me vient à contrecueur, it goeth agaynst my mynde.
Contredire, to gaynſay, too murmour, to withstand.
Contrediſant, ou qui contredit touſiours, a gaynſayer.
Contrée & pays, a land or countrey.
Contrefaire, to counterfeat, too make like.
Contrefaire quel qu'vn, to counterfeat a man.
Se contregarder, to keepe himſelfe, to ſpare himſelfe, to looke to himſelfe.
Contreporteur, a cariar aboute of letters or other things.
Contreuenir au droict, to withſtand the right.
Contriſter aucun, to make one ſorrowfull.
Se contriſter, to bee ſorrowfull, to bee carefull.
Controuerſe ou debat, controuerſie or ſtrife.
Controuuer & feindre, to inuent or faigne.
Controuuer quelque choſe en ſon eſprit, to imagine oute of our owne brayne.
Choſe controuuée, a thing fayned, or inuented.
Controuueur de mots, an inuentour of words.
Cōtrouueur de parolles & mē teur, a fayner, a lyer.
Conuenir & apointer de quelq̄ affaire qui eſtoit en doubte, to agree on things in controuerſie.
Faire bien conuenir, to make them well agree.
Conuenant à quelque affaire, fit for a thing.
Il conuient, it behoueth, it is cō uenient.
Cōuenable, Propre ou ſortable à quelque choſe, conuenient, apt, meete for a thing.
Cōuenancer, to promiſe, to make couenant.
Vn conuers, nouueau à la foy, a conuert, one newe come to the faith.
Conuerſer auec quelqu'vn, to be conuerſant with one, too keepe companie.
Conuerſation & familiarité, cō uerſation and familiaritie.
Se conuertir, to bee conuerted, to turne.
Cōuertir inimitiez en amitiez, to turne enimitie into friēdſhip.
Se conuertir en liqueur, to bee conuerted into liquor.
Se conuertir en ſel, to be conuerted into ſalt.
Conuier, Semondre à ſouper, to bid to ſupper.
Conuoitiſe qu'on a tant de bonnes choſes, que de mauuaiſes, concupiſcence.
Conuoy, a following or wayting on.
Cōuoy des obſeques d'vn treſpaſſé, to follow the dead corps, or to bring him home.
Conuoyer aucun par honneur, to beare one companie home.
Cophin, ou panier d'oſier, a baſket.
La copie & le double de quelq̄ eſcripture, the copie of a writīg
Abōdant & copieux en ſçauoir de diuerſes choſes, aboundant and plentiful in knowledge.
Copier, to copie or write out.
Du coq, herbe, an herbe called costmarie.
Coquelourdes, an herbe called of ſome Roſe perſeley.
Le coqueluchon d'vne cappe, & la cappe que les ſemmes portent ſur leurs teſtes pour la pluye, a cocks combe on a hood.
Vn coquemart ou vne chaudiere, a caudron.
Des coquerets, herbe, an herbe called Alkakengie.
La Coquille d'vn limaçon & sēblables, the ſhell of a ſnayle or ſhell fiſh.
Les coquilles de la noix, nut ſhels.
Coquin, a needie fellow, a begger.
Vne pierre qu'on appelle Corbeau ſortant de la muraille pour ſouſtenir vne poultre, a corbell, a ſtone ſet out of a wall to beare weight on.
Corbeille ou on met la paſture des beſtes, a basket to carrie beasts meat in.
Corbeille faicte d'oſier, a basket of oyſers.
Corbeille faicte de geneſt, a maūd.
Corbeillon, ou Picotin, a little basket.
La ligne ou le cordeau du charpentier, the carpentars ligne.
Cordelette, ou corde moindre qu'vn cable, a ſtring, a pack-threed, a corde.
Cordeur de terres, a bounder of landes.
Vn Cormorant, a fiſhe called a Cormorant.
Cornaline, pierre precieuſe, a ſtone called a Corneline.
La Corne du pied d'vne beſte, a beasts hoofe.
Cornet, ou trompe, an inſtrumēt called a cornet, a horne.
Vn Cornet de papier comme d'apoticaire, a cornet or coffin, ſuche as Grocers make of paper to put ſpice in.

Se Desfaire ſoymeſme, to make himſelfe away, to kill himſelfe.
Desfaicte, ou perte de bataille, the defeate or ouerthrowe of a battaill.
Desfacher, to take away greefe, to put away anger.
Desfricher, to ridde a ground of roots and thistles, to make it arable.
Soy Desfuler, to put off ones cap, to make obeiſance.
Deſgager, to fetch out of pleadge.
Deſgaigner vn glaiue, too vnſheth, to drawe a ſworde.
Se Deſgarnir de ſon armée, & la bailler à vn autre, to vnfurniſh.
Deſgarni & deſcouuert, vnfurniſht or lying open.
Se Deſgorger, to vomite, to ſpue out his venime.
Aiſé à Degouſter, & pour peu de choſe, one that will eaſily loth a thing: a nice or daintie perſon.
Deſgoutement de viandes, lothſomneſſe of meates.
Deſguiſement de marchandiſe, counterfeat or vntrue wares.
Desherité & priué de la ſucceſſion, diſherited, put from poſſeſſion.
Il eſt Deſia tard, it is late.
Deſioindre & ſeparer, to ſeuer to ſeparate.
Fort deſiré, much deſired, in good estimation.
Deſléer & deſtramper, to ſoake, to deleye.
Deſloger, to depart from home, to vnlodge.
ſe Deſmarier, to vnwed, to diuorſe
Deſmembrer, to diſmember, to teare in peeces.
Il l'a Demēti, he told him he lyed.
Deſmeſler, to rid, not to medle with a thing.
Vne grande Demeſure, without all meaſure
Deſmettre quelque mēbre hors de ſon lieu, to put out of ioynt, to misplace.
Membres Deſmis de leur lieu, & deſnouez, membres put out of ioynt or place.
Se Deſmouuoir de ſa conſtance, to remoue from his constancie.
Se Deſnouër quelque membre, to vnknit a bone, to put out of ioynt.
Deſnuër, to make naked, to ſpoyle
Deſobeir à ſon maiſtre, to diſobey, to be ſtubborne.
Deſordonné, diſordinate, without meaſure or order.
Deſordonnément aymer, too loue without meaſure.
Deſordre de toutes choſes, confuſion, diſorder.
Deſormais, but yet, for all that.
Deſpeçer, to cut in peeces, too breake on ſunder.
Deſpeçé à grans coups d'iniures, ſhaken vp with reuilings, ratled.
Deſpendre, to ſpend, to conſume, to wast away.
Deſpendre, diſſiper, gaſter, & conſommer ſes biens ou ſon patrimoine, to ſpend away all his inheritaunce.
La republique Deſpend de Brutus, the publike weale dependeth on Brutus.
A ſes Deſpens, at his own charge or perill.
Deſpenſeur, qui a la garde de la viande, a ſpencer.
Faire bonne deſpeche & ſe haſter, to dispatch, to make hast.
Deſeſpeſſir, eſclarcir vne choſe trop eſpeſſe, to make thin, too clarifie.
Deſpeſtrer aucun & deliurer, to rid one out of troubles,
Deſpeupler, to vnpeople, to wast to ſpoyle.
Deſpit, qui fe courouce aiſement, a ſpitefull fellowe.
Se Deſpiter, to ſpite, to anger.
Ie me Deſplay, it greeueth or diſpleaſeth mee.
Eſtre Deſplaiſant de quelq̄ choſe, to be displeaſed with a thīg.
Faire Deſplaiſir, to do one a diſpleaſure, to offend one.
Deſplāter, to pul vp by the roote.
Deſplier, to vnfold, ſometyme to make manifest.
Deſpliement & maniement de iambes, the folding or turning of the legges.
Deſpoiller, to ſpoyle, to vnclothe, to put off.
La Deſpouille des ennemis, the ſpoyle of enimies.
Deſpraué, ou Depraué, depraued, marred, corrupted.
Deſpriſer, to dispraiſe, to blame, to contemne, to dispiſe.
Deſpriſable, dequoy on ne doit faire compte, disprayſable.
Deſpriſement, a disprayſing, a cōtemning, a ſetting at naught.
Deſpuceler vne vierge, too defloure a mayden.
Deſridemēt, the wrincklīg of the skin.
Deſrobbeur & pilleur, a theef, a robber, a picker, a pilferer.
A la Deſrobée, priuily, ſecretly, by ſtelth.
Deſrondir quelque choſe, to bring out of compaſſe.
Deſrouler, to ſcoure, to furbiſh, to get out rust.
Deſrouiller, to roll out, to declare.
Deſruné, out of order, taken downe, taken in peeces.
Se Deſſaiſir, to forgoe, to let loſe.
Deſſerrer, to releaſſe, to vnſhut, to open.
Deſſeruir ſus table, to take vp table.
Deſſerte de table, the banket or after courſe.
Le deſſus de toutes choſes, & comme la face, the vpper part of a thing.
Deſteler les cheuaux, To loaſe horſes, or vnspang them from the carte.
Deſtendre, to ſtretche oute, to ſpreade.
Deſtiner choſes en ſoymeſme & propoſer, to apoynt, to purpoſe.
Deſtiné à la mort, appoynted to die.
Vne année deſtinée & fée à la diſtruction de la ville, a yeare appoynted to the destruction of the towne.
Deſtituer vn choſe commēcée, to diſappointe or make destitute.
Deſtorſé, ou deſtordement, wroong or writhed.
Deſtorſe, & fouruoyement, to ſtray, to wend out of the way.
Deſtour, lieu entre les montagnes ou on ſe retire, a by place betwene hilles, where men may hide them.
Deſtourber, to trouble, to diſturbe, to hinder.
Deſtourbier, ou deſtourbement a trouble, let, hindrance.
Vn diſtourbeur, qui par ſon caquet empeſche & deſtourbe aucune choſe, a troubleſome man, a prating fellow.
Deſtourner aucun, to diſſuade a man from his purpoſe.
Deſtourner aucun choſe, & la deſrobber, to conuey a thyng away.
Se deſtournér d'aucun, To forbeare ones companie.
Deſtourné, diſſuaded, turned from his purpoſe.
Qui deſtourne par parolles, A diſſuader.

Deſtournement d'eaües, a tu •
ning of the courſe of water an other waye.
Deſtrancher à coups de langue, To rebuke one ſharply, to rattle vp.

Deſtranché & deſpecé à gran • coups d'iniure, rattled vp with
reuilings.
Deſtremper & meſler enſemble, & ramollir, To ſoften, to mollifie, to allay as wine wyth water, to ſoake.
Deſtrempé & meſlé parmy d'autre, ſoaken, ſoftned.
Vn deſtroict, a ſtraight, a narrow place.
Le deſtroict des chemins, A ſtreight in the way.
Deſtrouſſement de gents, a robbing of men
Deſtruire, to destroy, to waſt, to ouerthrow.
Deſueloper, to vnwrap, to ſhewe forth, to vnfolde.
Se deſuoyer, to erre, to ſtraye, to wander.
Deſuoyement d'eſtomach, weakeneſſe of the ſtomack.
Vn det à ioüer, a dye, a payre of dyce.
Detailler & mettre en pieces, to hewe in pieces.
Detenir, To holde, to detaine, to occupie.
Determinance de quelque choſe, laquelle apres auoir eſté diſputée & debatue, eſt miſe à fin, The determining or ending of a thing.
Deterrer, to dig out of the groūd.
Detracter & meſdire d'autruy, to backbite, to ſpeake euill behinde ones backe.
Deualler, To let downe, to tumbled downe.
Deuancir aucun à courir, To out run one.
Deuenir corps, to wax a body.
De deuers Orient, towards the East.
Deuider dú fil par pelotons, To winde vp threede in bottomes.
Vn deuideur, ou deuidoir, a rele to winde threede on.
Vn deuin, a ſoothſayer, a geſſer.
Deuiſer, to talke, to deuiſe, to comfort.
Vn deuis & ordonnance, a deuiſe or appointment.
Deuorer, to deuoure, to ſwallow vp.
Deux à deux, two by two, by couples.
D'eulx, pour De eux, of them; or from them.
A dextre, on the right hande.
Dialectique, ce'ſt à dire, l'art de bien diſputer, Logike, or good order of disputation.
D'icy, ou Des icy, from hence.
Dicy à queltemps, Howe long? in what tyme.
Dicy en auant, from hence forwarde.
Diete & regime de viure, Diet dayly fare.
Diffamer quelqu'vn, to defume one, to ſlaunder one, to take away ones good name.
Differer & delayer, to deferre, to delay, to driue off.
Differer d'vn iour, to defer from day to day.
Vn different & debat, a debate, a ſtryfe; a contention.
Eſtre en different & diſcord, to be at variance, to diſagree.
Difficilement, hardly, ſcantly, with muche a doo.
Defforme, vnſemely, filthie, out of faſhion.
Digerir quand l'eſtomach cuit bien la viande qu'il a receüe, to digest.
Diligent & ſoigneux à faire quelque choſe, diligent, carefull, ſtudious, circumspect.
Dinandier ou Maignen, a copper ſmith, a tinker.
Dinanderie, a place where copper wares are ſolde.
Dire, to ſay, to ſpeake, to ſhew, to talke.
On Dit, it is ſayde abroade.
Dict commun, a worde, a common talke.
Mon Dire touche pluſieurs, my talke toucheth many.
Vn dicton de bon enſeignemēt, a ſentence.
Dicter & nommer à vn autre quelque choſe qu'il eſcriue, to endite letters.
Diſcerner, ſeparer l'vn d'auec l'autre, to diſcerne, to ſeparate the one from the other.
Diſcretion ou ſeparation, difference or ſeparating.
Diſcord ou diſſention, diſcorde, ſtrife, diſſention, diſagreement.
Diſcours deſprit de tous coſtez, quād il penſe à quelque choſe, to conſider well, to caste euery waye.
Faire diſcuſſion ſus les biens dé Debteur, aſſauoir s'il eſt ſoluable, to value the goodes of a detter, to knowe whether hee bee able to pay,
Vn Diſenier, a Captayne of ten menne.
Diſette, dearth, neede, penurie, pouertie, lacke.
Diſionction & ſeparation, to diuide, to ſeuer.
Prendre les diſmes, to receyue tenthes.

Diſpenſer de la loy, to dispence
with the lawe.
Diſpoſer & mettre par ordre, to dispoſe, appoint, or ſet in order.
Il eſt ainſi diſpoſé, Jt is ſo appoynted.
Diſpoſition & accidens, dispoſitions or inclinations of the heauens.
Diſputer, to dispute, to reaſon, to debate.
Diſſimuler & cacher quelq̄ choſe, to diſſemble or couer a thing.
Diſſouldre & abatre ou rompre l'entreprinſe d'aucun, to breke or diſſolue thenterpriſe of other
Diſſolus & maluiuans, of retchleſſe lyfe, diſſolute.
Diſtance ou eſpace, a diſtaunce or ſpace betwene.
Diſtillation d'humeurs, a diſtilling of humors from the head, a catharre.
Tapis à l'eſguille Diuerſifiez de couleurs, tapistrie ſet foorth with diuers colours.
Diuertir aucun de ſon propos, to turne one from his purpoſe, to chaunge their mynde.
Diuiſer & ſeparer, to diuide, to ſeparate, to parte.
Diuiſer par cy & par là, To diuide hither and thither.
Diuiſion & ſeparation, a diuiſion, a ſeparation.
Diuulguer quelque ſecret, to open a ſecrete, to blabbe.
Dizain, that containeth the numbre of tenne.
Docte & ſçauant, a lerned man, a man of knowledge.
Eſtre docile, eaſy to be taught.
Vn doigtier, a thimble, a fingerlyng.
Doler du bois, to hewe or ſquare tymber.
Doleur de corps & d'esprit, ſorow of mynde, payn of body.
Appaiſer la douleur d'aucun, to aſſwage ones griefe.
Se dolouſer, to moane, to bewaile.
Domicile, a houſe, an abydyng place.
Donq, ou Donques, then, therefore, Ergo.
Donner, to giue, to delyuer, to graunt.
Donné la premier de Ianuier, giuen the first of Januarie.
Donter, to ſubdue, to ouercome, to rule, to tame, to daunt.
Dorade, poiſ • on, a fiſhe of ſome thoughte to bee called a Gyltehead.
Doſt qu'vne femme baille à ſon mari pour ſon mariage, The dowrie that the wife giueth hir huſbande in mariage.

Douaire qui le mari baille à la femme, The dowrie or ioynter that the huſbande giueth vnto
the wyfe.
Le double de quelque eſcripture, The copie of a writing.
Doublement d'eſcripture, a copying out of a writing.
Mettre quelque choſe en doubt to put a thing in dout, to bring a matter in controuerſis.
Vne choſe doubteuſe, a doubtefull thing.
Vn douzain, a ſhilling, in France a ſoulz.
Dragée aux cheuaux, Prouender for horſes.
Petit Drapeau ou Drapelet, A cloute.
Dreſſer, to directe, to ſet vp.
Dreſſoir ou buffet, a Dreſſer, a court cubborde.
Tout drogue bon ou mauuaiſe, drougs, poticary ware.
Droictement à l'heur, iuste at that houre.
Conſeil droicturier, & qui va à la rigueur du raiſon, ſtraight counſell.
Dru & eſpez, thicke, as the falling downe of rayne.
Dru, comme il cheent dru, they fall thicke.
Duquel i'auoye acheté ceſte maiſon, Of whome J boughte this houſe.
Homme dur & rude, A harde man.
Coucher ſur la dure, to lye on the grounde.
Durer, to harden, to continue, to last long.
Durant ces iours là, during that tyme.
Longue durée, of long during or lasting.
Se duire & accouſtumer, To be enured with a thing.
Duire quelqu'vn à quelque choſe par accouſtumāce, to enure one by custome.
Duict à rendre l'equité, brought to yelde to right.
Diſenterie, ou flux de ventre auec le ſang que les Italiens appellent Caqueſangue, a perillous kinde of flixe.
Eclypſe de Lune, Eclipſe of the Moone.
Edenter, to daſh out ones teeth.
Edict, ordonnāce, ou commandement faict par le prince ou magiſtrat, an ordonnaunce, a commaundement, a proclamation, an iniunction.
L'edifice qui fait la maſſon & charpentier, the Maſon and carpenters building.
Effacer, to blot out, to deface.
Effaroucher, to become fierce, to become wilde.
Effaict que l'art faict, the effecte of the workmanſhip.
Mettre en effect, to brīg to effect
Eſprouuer par effect, To proue in effect.
Effeminer, to effeminate, to make womaniſh.
Effigie, an I mage, or lykeneſſe.
Effundrer, ou efuentrer, too vnbowell, to drawe a fiſhe.
l'Effort qu'ōn met à faire quelque choſe, the endeuour, or good will that one hath to doe a thing.
s'Efforcer, & trauailler à faire quelque choſe, to enforce, or labour to do a thing.
Vn Effronté & eshonté, braſen faced, ſhameleſſe.
Effuſion d'eauë, pourging out of water.
l'Eine, qui eſt vne partie du corps, the gryne.
Elle, C'eſt le feminin de Luy, ſhe, the feminine of hee.
Elle, comme Bailler les elles à vn cheual, to giue a horſe the head.
Emaillures d'or ou d'argent, bullions or riuets of golde or ſiluer.
Emanciper, to giue ouer, or ſet at freedome.
Embaboüiner, to deceyue, too bring into fooles paradiſe.
s'Embarquer, to embark, to take ſhip.
Embaumer des corps morts, to embaulme dead corpſes.
Embellir, to decke, to trim, to furniſh, to ſet forth.
Emboucher quelqu'vn, too inſtruct one before hand, too tell him his leſſon.

Emboucler, to boucle, to clapſe
togither.
Embraſer, to ſette on fire, to enflame.
Embraſſer, to coll, to clip, to embrace.
Embrocher de la chair, to ſpitte meat.
s'Embrouiller en quelq̄ affaire, to cōber himſelf with a matter.
s'Embucher, to lye in wayte or embuſhe.
Emmener auec ſoy, to lead with him, to carry abroade.
Emmener par force, to lead away by force.
Emmeubler & ameſnager ſa maiſon, to furniſh a houſe with ſtuffe.
Emoucer, to make dul or blunt
Empecher de faire quelq̄ choſe, to hinder, to let, to withstand.
Empeſtrer quelqu'vn, to pester, to trouble, to let, to hinder one.
Empereur, an Emperour, a head commaunder.
Empirer, to make worſe, to decay, to empayre.
s'Empirer, to waxe worſe and worſe.
Vn Employ iournel, quād on ſe ſert tous les iours d'vne choſe a dayly buſineſſe or occupatiō.
Employer & deſpendre à quelque choſe, to bestowe, to laye out on a thing.
s'Employer a faire quelque choſe, to giue himſelfe to doe ſome thing.
Ne s'Employer point, not to do his endeuour.
Employer tout le iour, to bestow all the daye.
Enuoyer à l'Emplete, trafiquer ça & là, to ſend about his buſineſſe.
Empoigner, to lay hands on, to catch.
Emporter, to carry away, too take away.
Empoule, a wheale, a blister, a puſhe, a bubble.
Empreindre, to print in, to preſſe in.
Empreincte & marque, a print or marke.
Empreſſer, to preſſe out, to thruſt togither, to ſquiſe.
Empriſonner, to empriſon, to lay in priſon.
Eſtre empriſonné, to be layd in priſon.
Emputer, to dilate or driue off the tyme.
En iouant, in iest, in playe.
Enaſer, to cut of ones noſe.
Encant, comme vendre à l'Encant, port ſale.
Encauer les nids des poulles, to make hennes nests in a wall.
Enceindre & entourer, to girt in, to compaſſe about.
Encenſiere, herbe, a kinde of Sauerie.
Eſtre Enchaine, to be tyed on a chayne.
Enchanter, to enchāt, to bewitch, to charme.
Encharger quelque choſe à aucun, to charge, to enioyne one the doing of a thing.
Enchaſſer en or, to chace in gold.
Mettre à l'Enchere, to rayſe the price, to make deere.
Encherir les viures d'vne armée, to rayſe the vitayles in an armie.
Enciſer les arbres, to cut trees about.
Encliner, to encline, to bend too.
Encliné vers terre, bent to the groundward.
Enclore, to encloſe, to parke in.
Les Encoigneures des parois, the corners of a wall.
Eſtre encombré de dueil & d'ennuy, to be compaſſed with ſorrowe and care.
Encourir des honneur, to run in ill name.
Encre dequoy on eſcrit, writing ynke.
Encrouſter ou creſpir, to perget, to make hard in a crust.
Encuſer, to diſcloſe, to appeache, to bewraye.
Eſtre endebté, to bee endetted, to enioye other mens goods, to bee in other mens daunger.
Endeſuer, to bee mad, to rage.
Endommager, to hurt, to hinder to dommage.
Se deſendormir, to fal on ſleape.
Endormiſſon & eſtonnemēt de membres, the ſleaping or benomneſſe of the members.
Endroit la maiſon, about the houſe.
Enduiſſon & frottemēt de quelque liqueur, an oyntement.
Enduit, ou Enduiſsō, ſoit de plaſtre, ou de chaux, & ſable, the plastring of a houſe.
Endurer & ſouffrir, to endure, to ſuffer, to beare.
Eſtre Enfermé à la clef, vnder locke and kaye.
Vne Enfermerie, a cloſet, a lodging for a ſicke man.
Enfermement, a cloſing or ſhutting vp.
s'Enfierir & s'enorguillir, to wax proud, to wax lofty.
Enfiler vne aiguille, tothreed a needle,
Enfondrer les nauieres, to ſinke ſhips, to drowne.
s'Enfondrer, to bee ſonke, too bee drowned.
s'Enfonſer, to ſinke to the bottom.
s'Efforcir, to waxe ſtrong, to take a good hart.
Enfoüir dedens terre, to digge vnder the ground.
s'Enfuir, to flee, to run away, to ſhun.
Engager, to gage, or to laye to gage.
Engarder & empeſcher q̄ quelque choſe ne ſe face, to withhold the doing of a thing.
Engeance, the ſeede or race of any thing.
Engin & inſtrument, an engine or instrument.
Engloutir, to ſwallowe vp, to deuoure.
Le vent s'Engouffre en ce lieu là, & s'entonne, the winde whirleth in that place.
Engourdi de froid, benoom with colde.
Engraiſſer, to fatten, to cram, to graze.
Engraiſſer vne beſte, to fatten a beast.
Engraiſſement de beſtes, too graze or fatten cattell.
s'Engroſſir, to waxe groſſe, too waxe thicke.
Engroſſiſſement de femelles, to be with child, to be with yong.
Faire Enhair & trouuer mauuais quelque choſe aux citoyens, to bring the people in hatred with a thing.
Enhardir, to harten, to bolden, to encourage.
s'Enhardir, to waxe hardy, too trust.
Enhorter, to exhort, to perſuade, to require.
Enioindre quelque choſe à faire to apoynt any thing to be done to enioyne, to commaund.
Enlaidir, to make ſoule, to make filthie, to raye.
Enlaidiſſement, a diſhonesting, a distayning, a defiling.
Enleuer, too rayſe vp, too heaue vp.
Petite Enleueure, & cōme enſleure qui ſe leue ſus le pain en cuisāt, a little bladder that riſeth on bread while it is baking.
Ennuy & faſcherie, heauineſſe, ſorrow, trouble, anger.
Ennuyer, to molest, to trouble, to weary one.
s'Ennuyer & faſcher, too bee weary of a thing.

Vn fatiſte, a player, a Poet.
Fruicts qui ſont fades, vnſauery frutes.
Fague, the necke piece of a Bore, the fag piece.
Faillir, to fayle, to erre, to lacke.
Faire, to do, to go about.
Faire quelq̄ choſe, to do a thing.
C'en eſt faict, it is done.
Vn Faiſceau de quelque choſe que ce ſoit, liée enſemble, a bunche, a bundle.
Il Falloit vſer de plus long exemples, it behoued to vſe longer examples.
Il Fault, it must, it behoueth.
La Famille & race, the houſe, kinred, the familie.
Vn Fan de biche ou autres beſtes, a faune.
Se faner, to rotte, to putrifie, to corrupt.
le Fanon d'vn boeuf, le peau qui luy pend ſoubs le long du col the dew lap of a rudder beast, hanging downe vnder hys necke.
Fantaſie & volonté d'vne perſonne, the fantaſie and minde of a body.
Faonner, to faune as does doe.
Vne Farce, a playe, an interlude.
Farceur, a player of ſuch playes.
Ioüer de Farces, qui repreſentēt contenances ſelon l'eſtat des perſonnes, a player, a counterfeater of perſonages.
De la Farce, a liuering, a pudding
Farcir & remplir, To ſtuffe, to franke, to feede.
Fardé, paynted, as ſome women vſe to paynt themſelues.
Fardement de vielles choſes, pour le mieux vendre, a painting or ſetting forth olde things to the ſhewe.
Vne Fardeau, a fardell, a truſſe, a burthen.
Faſcher ou ennuyer quelqu'vn, to anger or displeaſe one.
Tu me faſches & ennuyes, thou troublest me.
Faſeoles, a kind of ſmall pulſe.
Fau, vn arbre, a Beche tree.
Fauori, ou fauoriſé, in fauoure, fauoured.
Vne Faucille ou crochet, a ſicle, a hooke.
Faucon, oyſeau de proye, A Falcon.
Faulſer des lettres, to counterfeat letters.
Qui fait Faulſetez, he that committeth falſhode.
Faulte pour peché, fault, blame, offence.
Faulte ou diſette, wante, lacke, ſcarſitie.
Faulx, homme Faulx, A falſe man.
Vne Faux ou Faucille, a Sickle, a Sythe.
Fauue, ou Fauueau, a depe yealow, a bay.
Vne petite choſe noire qui eſt au cul d'vne Febue, the blacke ſpot at the tayle of the beane.
Vn Fauat de Febues, a ſtacke of beanes.
le Faiture de quelque choſe par laquelle on la met à eſtre, the making or workmanſhip of a thing.
Feé, & qui doibt aduenir par neceſſité, appointed, that must needes come to paſſe.
Fellure en pierre precieuſe, the vaynes in a precious ſtone.
Femelle, the ſhee of any thing.
Fendu en deux, cleft in two.
Fente, a cleft, a rift, a rent.
Fener ou fletrit, To wither away.
Feneſtré & percé, windowed or pierced through.
Vn fenil ou on garde le fein, A hay lofte.
Ferrer muls & cheuaux, To ſhoe-horſes or moyles.
Feries & iours de ceſſation, holy days, wakes.
Vn fermaillet qui ſe pend au col pour preſeruer de poiſon, a preſeruatiue to hang aboute ones necke agaynst poyſon.
La ferme du prince ou demaine the kings reuenue.
Vne Ferme, a ferme, a Mannour.
Le Fermiers du prince, the kings fermers.
Eſtre ferme & conſtant, To be ſtable, to be conſtant.
Fermer, to ſhut vp, to cloſe vp.
Fermement & cloſture de bouche, a ſtopping ones mouth.
Les • eſſes, the Buttockes, the breeche.
Feſſer, to breeche boys, to ſcourge them.
Le Feſte d'vn edifice, the ridge of an houſe.
Feſter, To keepe Holydaye, to feaste.
Feſtoyer aucun, to feast one, to cheere one.
Vn Feſtu, a ſtrawe or ruſhe, a mote.
Fiancer vne fille ou vne femme, to betrouth, to make ſure, too handfast.
Ficher, to fasten, to ſticke in, to ſet fast.
Fiction & controuuement, a thing feigned, an imagination.
Fiebure, ou Fieure, an ague, a feuer.
Fiens à fumer la terre, dong to dong the earth.
La Fiente & ordure d'vne beſte, the dong of a beast.
Soy Fier à quelqu'vn de quelque ſecret, to trust one with ſome ſecrete talke.
Fier & arrogant, proude, lofty, high minded.
Vn Filé & verueu à prēdre poiſſons, an angle or bayt to catch fiſhe.
Filet à Filet, thred by thred.
Filure & tiſſure de layne ou de ſoye, ſpinning.
La Filace qu'on met en la quenoüille, the flaxe that is put on the distaffe.
Les Filamens des veines, the ſtrings on vaynes.
Vne Fille, a daughter, a wenche.
La Fin de quelque choſe que ce ſoit, the ende of a thing.
A Fin que ie ne, &c. to the ende that. &c.

Finer, to ende, to determine, to
conclude.
Finablement, ou Finalement, finally, in ſumme.
Fin homme, a ſuttle, crafty or beguyling man.
Vn Flaccon, ou boutaille, a flagon, a bottell.
Flagorneur & rapporteur, a blab, a tale teller, a tale carrier.
Flambe, ou Flamme de feu, a flame of fire.
Flambeau, ou torche, a torche, a linke.
Flamboyer & reluire, to flame, to ſhine.
Flater, Qui eſt vn mot propre quand les chiens blandiſſent de la queue, too flatter, to faune as a dog doth.
Flatrer au front d'vne lettre chaulde, to marke one in the forehead with a hoate yron.
Flatré, marked for a naughtie packe.
Le Fleau & tendon ou ville de la vigne dont elle s'attache, the branche or ſhooting out of a vine.
Vne Fleche & vn traict, a ſhaft, an arrowe.
Flechir & ployer quelque choſe to bend, to bowe a thing.
Se Fleſtrir, to wither awaye, to drye vp.
Vne Flette, a lighter, a ſmall boate.
Fleurette, ou Fleuron, a little floure.

Fleute, ou Flute, ou Flageolet,
a flute, a whistle, a pype, a fife.
Fleuteur, ou Fluteur, a pyper, a fluter, a fife.
Fleuue ou riuiere, a floude or riuer.
Vn Floc & bouton de laine, a flocke of wolle.
Le Flot de la mer, the flowing of the Sea.
Flux de ventre, the flyxe, the laske.
Foin de pré, graſſe of the paſture.
Foires d'vne ville, the faire or marte of a towne.
Fomentation, a plaster that aſſuageth heat.
Le Fond de quelque choſe que ce ſoit, the ground of a thing, the bottome.
vn Fond, champ & piece de terre, ſoyle, a peece of ground.
Vn Fondement, a ground, a foū dation.
Se Fondre, to melt away, to conſume.
Vne Fontaine, a ſpring, a foū taine.
Vn Fontenier, a digger of welles, a ſeeker of ſprings.
De toute ma Force, with all my power.
Forcené, mad, furious, out of his wit.
Forces, ou ciſeaux, ſheares or ciſſers.
Forer, ou percer, to boare a hole.
Lieu Foreſtier & ſauuage, a wooddy and wild place.
Auoir Forfaict contre quelque loy impoſant peine, to forfait against the lawe.
Forge à fer, a ſmithes forge.
Forger & marteler, to forge or frame.
La Forme, façō & traict de quel que choſe, the forme, faſhion, or draught of a thing.
Fort robuſte & puiſſant, very ſtrong and mighty.
Vn Fort & camp arreſté, a fort or ſettled campe.
Vne Foſſe, a pit, a diche, a graue.
Foüet, ou eſcourgée, a whip or ſcourge.
Fouiller & cercher ſoigneuſement, to ſearche diligently.
Fouine, ou chat, ſelon aucuns, a beast called a foyne.
Fouir la terre, & creuſer, to dig or delue the earth.
Foule de peuple, a throng of people.
Fouler aucun, to oppreſſe one, to tread vnder foote.
Fournier, one that keepeth an ouen for folke to bake in.
Fourcher, quand la langue fourche, to ſtutte, to trip with the tong.
Fourmy, an ant, an emmont, a piſmere.
Fournier de quelque choſe, to furniſh, to make vp that wāteth
Fourrer, ou Iecter dedens, to thrust in, to throwe in.
Fourriers qui ordōnent les quar tiers, they that apoīt out groūd.
Se Fouruoyer, to ſtray, to erre.
Le Fouyer de la maiſon, fire.
Foy, quand on tient ſa promeſſe, faith.
Frain & mords d'vne bride, the bit of a bridle.
Franc, qui ne doibt point de tribut, free, at libertie, franke.
Franchement & ſans crainte, freely, without feare.
Frapper, to ſtrike, to knocke, to beate.
Frayer, & heurter contre la riue, to rap against the ſhore.
Frequenter, ou hanter quelque lieu, to frequent, to hant, to vſe a place.
Freſaye ou cheueche, a ſhreech howle.
Freſſure ou Freſure, the inwards or entrayles.
Freter vne nauire, to freighte a ſhip.
Fretiller, to waue, to moue, to wagge, to wauer.
Frez & nouellement faict, freſh, new done.
Vn Friand, Friolet, a likerouſe fellow, a ſweet lips.
Friche, comme, Terre delaiſſée en Friche, fallow, ground that lyeth fallowe.
Veſtements Fripez, clothes that haue bin worne.
Vn Fripier, a Seller of olde clothes.
Friuole, vayne, trifling, of no value.
Auoir Froid, to be a cold.
Froiſſer, to breake in peeces, to quaſhe aſunder.
Vn clou ou Froncle, a byle.
Vn Fronteau, a frontlet, a forehead cloth.
La Frontiere d'vne bride, the face part of the brydle.
Les Frontieres d'vn pais, the frontiers of a countrey.
Frotter de quelque liqueur, too rubbe with a water, to chafe, to ſoake.
Fruictier, that beareth frute, an orchard.
Fruſtrer & priuer aucū de quelque choſe, to frustrate, or diſapoint one.

Eſtre Fruſtré de ſon eſperance,
to be frustrate of the hope conceyued.
La Feuille des arbres, the leaues of trees.
Fueille, tant d'arbres que d'herbe, the leaues of trees or herbes.
Fueiller, ou iecter fueilles, to bring forth leaues.
Les Fueilles d'vn liure, the leaues of a booke.
Fueilletter les liures, to turne ouer bookes.
Fuir, to flee, to run away.
Fuir & euiter, to flee, to ſhun, to auoyde.
Fumerles Oliuiers, to dong Olyue trees.
Fumement de terre, donging of ground.
Vn Fuſil, a fuſill to ſtrike fire in a tinderboxe.
Vn Fuſt, a ſtaffe, a ſtake.
Vne Fuſte legere, a foyst or light ſhip.
Fuſtoine, ou bombaſin, & toute autre choſe faicte de cotton, fustian.
Fut, ſeeke Eſtre. Il fut, he was.
Gabion, a basket of earth, ſuch as they vſe for defence in warre
Gage, loyer & ſalaire qu'on dō ne pour la beſongne, wages, reward in respect of worke.
Le Gage qu'on met on ieu, a gage, a paune.
Les Gages des Genſdarmes, ſoldiours wages.
Gager contre aucun, to laye a wager, to gage.
Faire Gageure & mettre en ieu, to wage, to paune.
Gaigner, to winne, to gayne, to profite.
Gaigner vn mal, to gette a diſeaſe.
Du Galbanon, a kinde of gum, iſſuing out of an herbe.
Galle, a galling, a fretting, a rubbing of the skin.
Gallée de trois raines pour bāc, a galley with. 3. rewes of ores.
Gallee de cinq rames pour bāc, a galley with. 5. rewes of ores.
Gallion, ou Brigantin, vne ſorte de nauiere ainſi nommée, a Galliot, a Brigandine.
Gallerie, ou on ſe pourmene, a gallery, a walking place.
Galloches, a kīd of ſhoe, a pattin
Gallonner & frotter fort en agminotant, to clap on the back, to cheriſh.
Garance, herbe, madder whiche Diers vſe.
La Garde du corps d'vn prince, a Kings garde.
La Garde du corps d'vn capitaine, a Captaynes warde.
Garder, to warde, to keepe, to defend, to ſheeld.
Bailler en Garde, to giue in ward to commit.
Garde que, &c, take heed that, beware least, &c.
Gardeur de beſtial, a hearde, a pastour.
Gardien ou Gardienne, a warden, a keeper.
Vn Gardemanger, a cubbord, an aumbrie.
La Gargouille ou ſiflet, a whiſtle
Garnir d'or, to garniſh with gold
Garnir ſa maiſon, to furniſhe or trim a houſe.
La Garniſon qu'on met en vne ville, the garriſon of a towne
Garſon fillette, both boye and wench.
Garsōner la femme d'autruy, to haue to do with an other mans wife.
Vne Gaſche, an oare, a skull.
Gaſcher du plaſtre, to ſpred a plaſter.
Gaſpiller ſon propre & deſpendre follement, to waſte and ſpend away his goods.
Vn Gaſteau, ou tourteau, a cake.
Gaſter, to marre, to ſpill, to wast to conſume.
La gauche ou main ſeneſtre, the left hande.
Gaucher ou tortuer, To wring or bende.
Gaudir & faire groſſe cher, to be frolyke, to be liuely.
Se gaudir d'aucū, to iest with one to floute.
Par gaudiſſerie, in iest, or floutingly.
Vne Gaule, a ſtaffe, a cudgell.
La Gaule Celtique, The farther part of Fraunce.
Gazouiller, To whiſtle, ſing, chirp, or warble, as birdes do.
Gect, ou Iect, a throw or cast at dice.
Geene, ou Gehenne, torture ou queſtion, a racke, a place of torment.
Geiner, ou Geheinner, quelqu'vn, to racke one.
Gelinier, a hen houſe, a roust.
Gendre, my ſonne in lawe, my daughters huſband.
Du geneſt, an herbe ſo called.
Vn Gent & nation, a nation, a kin • ed.
Vn Gendarme ou homme de guerre, a ſouldiour.
La Gendarmerie, the rout of ſoldiours.
Gent miſte & propre, a propre man, a coint fellow.
Gentienne herbe, an herbe called Gentian.
Gentillement, Gentiment, ou Gentement, handſomely, proprely, featly.
Gerbe de blé, an eare, an eare of corne.
Germain, engendré de meſme germe, come of the ſame ſtock that J am.
Gemence & ſemence des arbres, The ſprigs or ſproutes of trees.
Germer, to bud out, to ſproute.
Sa femme giſt, his wyfe lyeth in.
Geſte, maintien, contenance, mine, gesture, behauiour, demeanour.
Getter quelque ſomme, to caſte a ſumme.
Gibbeciere, a pouche, a bag, a purſe.
Gibbet, a gibbet, a payre of gallowes.
Gibbier, all kind of fleſhe meate.
Glacé de tous coſtez, yeed, or froſen about.
Gladiateur, ioüer d'eſpée, ou eſcrimeur, a maister of fence, a fence man.
Glais, ou Glayeul, herbe, an herbe ſo called.
Vu glaiue, a ſworde, a glaiue.
La Glane qu'on a amaſſé, apres moiſſonieurs, gleaning.
Glappir comme vn chein ou regnard, to barke like a dogge or foxe.
Gletteron, ou Glouteron & Bar dane, herbe, a burre.
Glaſon ou motte, a turfe, a clod.
Gloire & louange par biē faire glorie, prayſe.
Glorieux, qui fait tout pour auoir gloire, glorious, proude.
Eſtre Glorieux, to bee proude, hautie.
Se glorifier & vanter, to brag, to boast.

Gloſſer comme les gelines, to
clock lyke a henne.
Gober, to ſwallow vp, to deuour
Vn godet & tout autre vaiſſeau de terre cuict, a Goddet, a ſtone cuppe.
Goffre & ſemblable qu'on bail le à petits enfants, a wafre.
Vn golfe de mer, a gulfe.
Les gons d'vne porte, the hooks of a doore.
Gorgerette, a gorget, a Lawne wherewith women couer their pappes.
Vn gorgias ou collet de femme a gorget.
Qui eſt Gorrier, trim, fine, feate.
Le Goſier ou Gauion, the throte.
Deuenir gourd & roide de force de froidure, crainte, ou autre aduenture, to waxe ſtiffe with colde.
La Gourme qui vient aux cheuaux, horſes fomyng at the mouth.
Gouſſe de febues, a beane cod.
Le Gouſter, ou reciner, an after noones banket.
Gouttes nouées ou crampes, the goute, the crampe.
La Goutte és mains, the goute in the handes.
La Goutte és pieds, the goute in the feete.
Vn Gouteron, ou burette, an ewer, a cruet.
Le Gouuernal d'vne nauire, the rudder of a ſhip.
Gouuerner, to gouern, to rule, to guyde.
Gouuernante, ou gouuernereſſe, a gouerneſſe, a woman ruler.
Guerdonner & recompenſer, to reward, to recompence.
Se guermenter, To lamente, to grone.
Guerpir ſon pais, & s'en aller habiter en terre eſtrange, to, forſake the countrey.
Gueſde, woad, ſuch as diers vſe.
Le Guet de nuict, The nighte watche.
Vne guette ou eſpie, a watchman, a ſpiall.
Guetter, To watche, to marke, to ſpie, to prie.
Guetteur de chemins, a robber by the high way.
Vn Guide qui meine autruy, a leader, a guide, a lodeſman.
Vne Guilée, a ſhowre of raine.
Viure a la guiſe d'autruy, guyſe, maner or faſhion, to liue after the maner of other.
Habiller, to cloath, to trimme, to furniſhe.
Habiter, to remayne, to dwell, to inhabite.
Les habitants d'un pays, the inhabitantes of a countrey.
s'Habituer & accouſtumer, to ſettle, to enure.
Hacher menu, to chop in peeces, to ſhread.
Vn haim, ou Hameſſon, a hook.
Halecret, & toute armure de corps, a corſlet.
Haler pour tirer en amont, To pull vp, to hale.
Haleter, to gaspe, to drawe the breath.
Hauap ou taſſe à boire, a Tankarde, a iacke.
La Hante ou fuſte d'vne iaueline, ou autre baſton, the ſtaffe of a iauelyne or other weapon.
Vne Har, Hars, ou Hart, a with made of a greene ſticke.
Harangue, a declaration, an oration, a tale.
Vn Haras, a hearde of horſes and mares.
Harceler, to vexe, to trouble, to annoy.
Harer les chiens, to cheriſh dogs to ſette them togither by their eares, to clap their backes.
Harnois à la legere, a light harneſſe.
Vn home tout haſlé, a man all to be ſunburned.
Vn haſle, a ſpit or broache.
Se Haſter d'aller, to make hast, to make ſpede.
Hau, a manner of calling, a howe;
Hau, c'eſt tresbien fait, Howe, well done.
Hau mon pere, Haw father heare ye?
Hautain, loftie, higher in the in-ſteppe.
Haultement prononcer quelque vers, to pronounce a verſe aloude.
Haulſer, to ſet vp, to ſet aloft.
Vn haure, a hauen, an harbour for a ſhippe.
De l'Hebene, a wod called heben
Hennir, to neigh like a horſe.
Toute ſorte d'herbe, All ſortes of herbes.
Vn here, ou eſtamine, ou ſaz, a boulter.
La Herſe de la porte d'une ville, a port eulleys.
Herſer & couurir la ſemence, to harrow the grounde.
Se heruper, to ſet vp the briſtles.
Bon Heur, good hap, good fortune.
A ceſte Heure, at this tyme.
Heurt, a blowe, a daſhe, a ſtroke.
Heurter ou frapper à la porte, to knocke at the dore.
Heurter & trebucher, to ſtrike downe, to ouerthrowe.
Vne Hie de quoy on bat le paué, & enfōſe on les pilotis en terre, a pauiers betle.
Hierce, vne ſorte de liarre, yuie.
Hipothequer & aſlubiectir au payement d'aueune choſe, to laye a paune to gage.
l'Hiſtoire des choſes ſaictes d'an en an, a ſtorie, a cronicle.
Hobin, a horſe called a hobbie.
Hodé, c'eſt à dire, Las ou laſſé, wearie.
Ho, ho, ſi toſt, what ſo ſoone?
Homicide, ou meurtre, a manqueller, a murtherer.
Hon, hon, quād on a petit à petit apperceu quelque mal, a ha?
Honneſte homme, louable, & de vertu, de bonne reputation, an honest man, and of good name.
Honneſte hōme & courtois, an honest and curteous man.
Honneſte mignon & ioli, an honest compaignon.
Eſtre Honni & à deshonneur, to bee defamed, to haue ones honesty ſtayned.
Le Hoquet, the hick op, yexing.
Hornus vn tel, excepting ſuch a one.
Vn Hoſte ou Hoſtelier, an hoſt.
Hoſtel de ville, a towne houſe, a guyld hall.
Hoſtelerie, an Inne, a table houſe, a tauerne.
Vne Hoüe, ou beſche, a pickax.
Houer la terre, to dig the groūd, to delue.
Vne Houſſe, the harneſſe of a horſe.
Vne Huche, a hutch, a cheste.
d'Huis en Huis, from dore to dore.
Huiſſier, ou Sergeant, an huſher, a ſergeant, a porter.
Vn Humet, a broth, a ſupping.
Hupe, a bird called a houpe.
Hydropique, one that hath the dropſie.

list.head: I ante A.
list.item: IA, comme, Il y a Ia deux Ans que, &c. already: It is already twoo yeares.
Vne Iachere, terre qu'on laiſſe repoſer en friche, fallowe ground.
Vne Iacinthe, a precious ſtone called a Iacinct.
Iadis, ou le tēps Iadis, heretofore
Ialoux, qui craint que ce qu'il aime ne ſoit commun à autruy, ialous.
La Iambe depuis le genouil iuſques en bas, the leg from the knee downward.
Vn Iambon, a peſtle of porke, a gammon of Bacon.
les Iantes d'vne roue, the ſpokes of a wheele.
Le mois de Ianuier, the moneth of Januarie.
Iarcer, Se Iarcer, too cleaue, to rent.
Iardin à herbes & arbres, a kitchin garden.
Iardin ou petit verger, a little garden.
Iargon, a counterfeat ſpeeche, pedlers Frenche.
Le Iarret, the houghes, the hammes.
Iaſer, to talke, to chat, to prate.
Vn Iauelot à darder, a dart.
Iauelle, ou boteau, a bockle, a truſſe, a bundell.
